oop iteration behavior, crash recovery, default behavior\n\nThe story leverages existing infrastructure already built in stories 4-1 (DispatchOptions.sessionId), 1-3 (TaskCheckpoint.session_id), and 2-1 (workflow schema session enum).\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **No problems encountered.** Epic definition was clear and unambiguous for story 4-2.\n- **Workarounds applied:** None.\n- **Risks identified:**\n  - The story creates a new `session-manager.ts` module rather than adding logic directly to `agent-dispatch.ts`. This is intentional per the anti-pattern in story 4-1 (\"Do NOT import from workflow-state\"), but the developer must understand that the workflow-engine (story 5-1) is the orchestrator that ties session-manager + agent-dispatch + workflow-state together. If 5-1 is not implemented correctly, session boundaries won't work end-to-end even though the unit tests pass.\n  - All ACs are `test-provable` because session-manager operates on in-memory WorkflowState objects. True end-to-end session boundary behavior (SDK actually resuming a session) is only testable at integration level in story 5-1.\n- **Observations:**\n  - Story 4-1 already implemented the `resume` passthrough in agent-dispatch.ts (line 135) and defined `DispatchOptions.sessionId`, so this story's scope is narrower than the epic text suggests -- it's primarily about the lookup/persistence logic, not the dispatch mechanics.\n  - The `TaskCheckpoint` in workflow-state.ts already has `session_id?: string`, so no schema changes are needed.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 13\n- By tool: Read: 8, Glob: 3, Grep: 1, Bash: 1, Write: 1, Skill: 1 (total including skill invocation: 15)\n- Largest Bash outputs: `git log --oneline -5` (~5 lines)\n- Files read: 11 unique, 11 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: None. Each read targeted a distinct artifact needed for story context."}],"totalDurationMs":134274,"totalTokens":65432,"totalToolUseCount":22,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"