{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014SSA5XiyTbGcfJvd2ibrBB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 4.2: Session Boundary Management\n2\t\n3\tStatus: review\n4\t\n5\t## Story\n6\t\n7\tAs a developer,\n8\tI want session boundaries configurable per task,\n9\tso that context resets and continuity are controlled by the workflow definition.\n10\t\n11\t## Acceptance Criteria\n12\t\n13\t1. **Given** a task with `session: fresh` in the workflow YAML\n14\t   **When** `dispatchAgent()` is called for that task\n15\t   **Then** the SDK `query()` is invoked with no `resume` option (a brand-new session is started)\n16\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n17\t\n18\t2. **Given** a task with `session: continue` in the workflow YAML\n19\t   **When** `dispatchAgent()` is called for that task and a previous session ID exists for that task+story combination\n20\t   **Then** the SDK `query()` is invoked with `resume` set to the previous session ID\n21\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n22\t\n23\t3. **Given** a task with `session: continue` but no previous session ID exists (first invocation)\n24\t   **When** `dispatchAgent()` is called\n25\t   **Then** a fresh session is started (no `resume` option passed) and the resulting session ID is stored for future continuations\n26\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n27\t\n28\t4. **Given** any `dispatchAgent()` call that completes (success or failure)\n29\t   **When** the result is returned\n30\t   **Then** the returned `DispatchResult.sessionId` is recorded in `workflow-state.yaml` under the corresponding `TaskCheckpoint.session_id` field\n31\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n32\t\n33\t5. **Given** a `session: continue` task across a crash-recovery restart\n34\t   **When** the engine resumes and `dispatchAgent()` is called for the continued task\n35\t   **Then** the session ID is retrieved from the persisted `workflow-state.yaml` (not just in-memory state) and passed as `resume`\n36\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n37\t\n38\t6. **Given** a `session: fresh` task in a loop block (e.g., retry)\n39\t   **When** the loop repeats the task for a second iteration\n40\t   **Then** a new session is started each iteration (no `resume`), and each iteration's session ID is independently recorded\n41\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n42\t\n43\t7. **Given** a `session: continue` task in a loop block\n44\t   **When** the loop repeats the task for a second iteration\n45\t   **Then** the session ID from the previous iteration of the same task+story is passed as `resume`\n46\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n47\t\n48\t8. **Given** a workflow where `session` is not specified for a task\n49\t   **When** the task is dispatched\n50\t   **Then** the default `session: fresh` behavior is used (per the workflow JSON schema default)\n51\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n52\t\n53\t9. **Given** unit tests for session boundary management\n54\t   **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n55\t   **Then** tests pass at 80%+ coverage for the session boundary logic covering: fresh dispatch (no resume), continue dispatch (resume with session ID), fallback to fresh when no prior session, session ID persistence in workflow-state, crash recovery session retrieval, loop iteration fresh/continue behavior, and default to fresh when session field omitted\n56\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n57\t\n58\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n59\t\n60\t- [x] Task 1: Create session manager module (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4, #8)\n61\t  - [x] Create `src/lib/session-manager.ts`\n62\t  - [x] Define `SessionBoundary` type: `'fresh' | 'continue'`\n63\t  - [x] Define `SessionLookupKey` as `{ taskName: string; storyKey: string }` to identify a task+story combination\n64\t  - [x] Implement `resolveSessionId(boundary: SessionBoundary, key: SessionLookupKey, state: WorkflowState): string | undefined` — returns undefined for fresh, looks up last session ID for continue\n65\t  - [x] Implement `recordSessionId(key: SessionLookupKey, sessionId: string, state: WorkflowState): WorkflowState` — writes session ID into the corresponding TaskCheckpoint\n66\t\n67\t- [x] Task 2: Integrate session manager with agent-dispatch (AC: #1, #2, #3)\n68\t  - [x] Update `dispatchAgent()` caller contract — the workflow engine (story 5-1) will call `resolveSessionId()` before dispatch and pass the result via `DispatchOptions.sessionId`\n69\t  - [x] Verify that `agent-dispatch.ts` already passes `options.sessionId` as `resume` to the SDK query (it does — line 135)\n70\t  - [x] Verify that `agent-dispatch.ts` already handles the `sessionId` being `undefined` (no resume) — confirm by reading the existing spread: `...(options?.sessionId ? { resume: options.sessionId } : {})`\n71\t\n72\t- [x] Task 3: Implement session ID persistence in workflow-state (AC: #4, #5)\n73\t  - [x] Verify that `TaskCheckpoint` already has `session_id?: string` field (it does)\n74\t  - [x] Implement helper `getLastSessionId(state: WorkflowState, taskName: string, storyKey: string): string | undefined` — searches `tasks_completed` array in reverse for matching task_name+story_key with a session_id\n75\t  - [x] The workflow-engine (story 5-1) will call `writeWorkflowState()` after each dispatch — this story ensures the `session_id` field is populated on the checkpoint\n76\t\n77\t- [x] Task 4: Handle loop iteration session behavior (AC: #6, #7)\n78\t  - [x] For `session: fresh` in loops: `resolveSessionId()` returns undefined regardless of iteration count\n79\t  - [x] For `session: continue` in loops: `resolveSessionId()` returns the session ID from the most recent checkpoint for that task+story pair (which may be from a previous loop iteration)\n80\t  - [x] Ensure `getLastSessionId()` finds the most recent entry (reverse search handles multiple loop iteration checkpoints)\n81\t\n82\t- [x] Task 5: Write unit tests (AC: #9)\n83\t  - [x] Create `src/lib/__tests__/session-manager.test.ts`\n84\t  - [x] Test: `resolveSessionId('fresh', ...)` returns undefined regardless of state\n85\t  - [x] Test: `resolveSessionId('continue', ...)` returns undefined when no prior checkpoint exists\n86\t  - [x] Test: `resolveSessionId('continue', ...)` returns session ID from matching checkpoint\n87\t  - [x] Test: `resolveSessionId('continue', ...)` returns most recent session ID when multiple checkpoints exist (loop iterations)\n88\t  - [x] Test: `recordSessionId()` populates session_id on the correct checkpoint\n89\t  - [x] Test: `getLastSessionId()` returns undefined when no matching checkpoint\n90\t  - [x] Test: `getLastSessionId()` returns most recent match (reverse order)\n91\t  - [x] Test: crash recovery scenario — session ID retrieved from deserialized state\n92\t  - [x] Test: default session boundary (fresh) produces no resume\n93\t  - [x] Verify 80%+ coverage on `session-manager.ts`\n94\t\n95\t## Dev Notes\n96\t\n97\t### Module Design Decision\n98\t\n99\tSession boundary management is implemented as a separate `session-manager.ts` module rather than modifying `agent-dispatch.ts` directly. Rationale:\n100\t\n101\t1. `agent-dispatch.ts` is intentionally stateless (it does not import `workflow-state`) — per story 4-1 anti-patterns\n102\t2. Session lookup requires reading `WorkflowState`, which is a different concern from SDK invocation\n103\t3. The workflow-engine (story 5-1) orchestrates the flow: resolve session ID -> dispatch agent -> record session ID -> write state\n104\t\n105\tThe `agent-dispatch.ts` module already supports session continuation via `DispatchOptions.sessionId` → `resume` (implemented in story 4-1, line 135). This story adds the logic to decide WHEN to pass a session ID and WHERE to find/store it.\n106\t\n107\t### How Session Boundary Works End-to-End\n108\t\n109\t```\n110\tworkflow-engine (story 5-1) calls:\n111\t  1. resolveSessionId(task.session, { taskName, storyKey }, currentState)\n112\t     → returns sessionId or undefined\n113\t  2. dispatchAgent(definition, prompt, { sessionId })\n114\t     → agent-dispatch passes sessionId as `resume` to SDK\n115\t  3. recordSessionId({ taskName, storyKey }, result.sessionId, currentState)\n116\t     → updated state with session_id on checkpoint\n117\t  4. writeWorkflowState(updatedState)\n118\t     → persisted to disk for crash recovery\n119\t```\n120\t\n121\t### Session ID Lookup Strategy\n122\t\n123\tThe `tasks_completed` array in `WorkflowState` stores all checkpoints including loop iterations. For `session: continue`, the lookup searches this array in reverse to find the most recent checkpoint matching both `task_name` and `story_key`. This naturally handles:\n124\t- First invocation: no match found, falls back to fresh\n125\t- Loop iterations: most recent checkpoint from previous iteration found\n126\t- Crash recovery: checkpoints persisted, so session ID survives restart\n127\t\n128\t### Existing Code That Already Supports This\n129\t\n130\t- `agent-dispatch.ts` line 135: `...(options?.sessionId ? { resume: options.sessionId } : {})` — already passes session ID as `resume`\n131\t- `workflow-state.ts` `TaskCheckpoint` interface: already has `session_id?: string`\n132\t- `workflow.schema.json` task definition: already has `session: { enum: [\"fresh\", \"continue\"], default: \"fresh\" }`\n133\t- `templates/workflows/default.yaml`: all tasks use `session: fresh`\n134\t\n135\t### What This Story Does NOT Do\n136\t\n137\t- Does NOT modify `agent-dispatch.ts` — it already handles session IDs via options\n138\t- Does NOT implement the workflow-engine orchestration loop (that's story 5-1)\n139\t- Does NOT generate trace IDs (that's story 4-3)\n140\t- Does NOT create source-isolated workspaces (that's story 4-4)\n141\t- Does NOT implement retry/finding injection (that's story 5-2)\n142\t\n143\t### Anti-Patterns to Avoid\n144\t\n145\t- **Do NOT add workflow-state imports to agent-dispatch.ts** — keep dispatch stateless\n146\t- **Do NOT cache session IDs in module-level variables** — always read from WorkflowState for crash recovery safety\n147\t- **Do NOT mutate WorkflowState in place** — return new state objects from `recordSessionId()`\n148\t- **Do NOT add retry logic** — that's the engine's responsibility\n149\t\n150\t### Dependencies from Previous Stories\n151\t\n152\t- **Story 4-1** created `agent-dispatch.ts` with `DispatchOptions.sessionId` and `DispatchResult.sessionId` — this module provides the logic to populate `DispatchOptions.sessionId`\n153\t- **Story 1-3** created `workflow-state.ts` with `TaskCheckpoint.session_id` and `writeWorkflowState()`/`readWorkflowState()` — this module reads/writes session IDs via the state\n154\t- **Story 2-1** created the workflow schema with `session: fresh | continue` — this module interprets that field\n155\t\n156\t### Project Structure Notes\n157\t\n158\t- New file: `src/lib/session-manager.ts` — session boundary resolution and session ID tracking\n159\t- New test file: `src/lib/__tests__/session-manager.test.ts`\n160\t- No modifications to existing source files\n161\t- Aligns with architecture pattern: each module in `src/lib/` is one file with co-located test\n162\t\n163\t### Testing Strategy\n164\t\n165\tMock `WorkflowState` objects directly — no file I/O mocking needed since session-manager works with in-memory state objects. The workflow-engine (story 5-1) handles the read/write lifecycle.\n166\t\n167\t### References\n168\t\n169\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-v2.md#Story 4.2: Session Boundary Management]\n170\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#AD1: Module Boundaries — agent-dispatch]\n171\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#Implementation Patterns — Session boundary enforcement]\n172\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-evaluator-redesign.md#FR20 — Session boundaries]\n173\t- [Source: src/lib/agent-dispatch.ts — DispatchOptions.sessionId, line 135 resume passthrough]\n174\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-state.ts — TaskCheckpoint.session_id field]\n175\t- [Source: src/schemas/workflow.schema.json — session enum definition]\n176\t- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-1-agent-dispatch-module-sdk-integration.md — predecessor story]\n177\t\n178\t## Dev Agent Record\n179\t\n180\t### Agent Model Used\n181\t\n182\tClaude Opus 4.6 (1M context)\n183\t\n184\t### Debug Log References\n185\t\n186\tNone required — no debugging needed. All tests passed on first run.\n187\t\n188\t### Completion Notes List\n189\t\n190\t- Created `src/lib/session-manager.ts` with three exported functions: `resolveSessionId`, `recordSessionId`, `getLastSessionId`\n191\t- Defined `SessionBoundary` type (`'fresh' | 'continue'`) and `SessionLookupKey` interface\n192\t- `resolveSessionId('fresh')` always returns undefined (new session); `resolveSessionId('continue')` looks up most recent session ID via reverse search on `tasks_completed`\n193\t- `recordSessionId` returns a new WorkflowState (immutable) with the session ID appended as a new TaskCheckpoint\n194\t- `getLastSessionId` does reverse linear search on `tasks_completed` matching both `task_name` and `story_key`\n195\t- Verified `agent-dispatch.ts` line 135 already passes `sessionId` as `resume` option to SDK `query()`\n196\t- Verified `TaskCheckpoint` already has `session_id?: string` field in `workflow-state.ts`\n197\t- 22 unit tests covering all 9 acceptance criteria, including crash recovery and loop iteration scenarios\n198\t- 100% coverage (statements, branches, functions, lines) on `session-manager.ts`\n199\t- Full regression suite: 152 test files, 3855 tests, all passing\n200\t\n201\t### Change Log\n202\t\n203\t- 2026-04-02: Story 4.2 implemented — session boundary management module with full test coverage\n204\t\n205\t### File List\n206\t\n207\t- `src/lib/session-manager.ts` (new)\n208\t- `src/lib/__tests__/session-manager.test.ts` (new)\n209\t- `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/4-2-session-boundary-management.md` (modified)\n210\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01N6moxj4qqjLtwBuA4vgPGH","session_id":"45fbbef5-e9ca-4512-91b9-2760b179ad44","uuid":"3b92f26d-b4a0-4afa-a45d-dc2060b6881a","timestamp":"2026-04-02T20:17:02.761Z"}
